<p><b>William Philip Gramm</b> (born <span class="mw-formatted-date" title="1942-07-08"><span class="mw-formatted-date" title="07-08"><a href="/wiki/July_8" title="July 8">July 8</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/1942" title="1942">1942</a></span>, in <a href="/wiki/Fort_Benning,_Georgia" title="Fort Benning, Georgia" class="mw-redirect">Fort Benning</a>, <a href="/wiki/Georgia_(U.S._state)" title="Georgia (U.S. state)">Georgia</a>, USA) is a <a href="/wiki/US" title="US" class="mw-redirect">US</a> <a href="/wiki/Politician" title="Politician">politician</a>, who has served as a <a href="/wiki/Democratic_Party_(United_States)" title="Democratic Party (United States)">Democratic</a> <a href="/wiki/United_States_House_of_Representatives" title="United States House of Representatives">Congressman</a> (1978–1983), a <a href="/wiki/Republican_Party_(United_States)" title="Republican Party (United States)">Republican</a> <a href="/wiki/Congressman" title="Congressman" class="mw-redirect">Congressman</a> (1983–1985) and a Republican <a href="/wiki/United_States_Senate" title="United States Senate">Senator</a> from <a href="/wiki/Texas" title="Texas">Texas</a> (1985–2002). He was a senior economic adviser to <a href="/wiki/John_McCain" title="John McCain">John McCain</a>'s presidential campaign from the summer of 2007 until July 18, 2008.</p>
